This research project seeks to develop new smart sensor technology for a widely-used clinical procedure called endoscopy, which is the most critical component in minimum- and non-invasive robotic procedures. Robotic medical diagnosis and surgery offer significant benefits both to the patient by minimizing damage and hence reducing recovery time, and to the clinician by enhancing his/her operation accuracy, dexterity, and efficiency.

Specifically, in this project, we have investigated the science and technologies needed to create a new 3-D imaging technology based on the latest advances in silicon photonics, 3-D integration, and imaging analysis techniques. The fully-integrated sensor device prototypes have been fabricated and assembled in the PIs' laboratories, and then tested experimentally. The algorithms and computation schemes for 3-D image and video analyses have been been developed and demonstrated. The vertically integrated research activities span research areas in devices, circuits, systems, and software. The multidisciplinary research team consisted of researchers from Electrical and Computer Engineering, Computer Science, and medicine. The research outcomes of this project have generated significant impacts on future optical imaging and communication systems, and potentially lead to new research and real-world applications.

In the last 4.5 years, the research team conducted research activities in a broad range of scientific and engineering areas, including photonic devices, circuits design, system integration, prototype development, control algorthms, compute architecture, and image/video analyses. This research project achieved the following major scientific findings and innovations:

- Invented a new architecture for integrated otical phased array (OPA) devices; Invented several new device and circuit techniques to improve the performance of integrated OPA devices;

- Developed 3 generations of photonic integrated circuits (PIC) for free-space optical (FSO) imaging, which have been fabricated using advanced silicon photonics technologies at commercial foundries including AIM Photonics;

- Developed several experimental test setups (testbeds) for the FSO imaging and communication experiments on our prototype devices and systems;

- Demonstrated FSO imaging and communications using the prototype devices, systems, and testbeds;

- Developed several 3D image and video analysis algorithms;  

- Published over 30 technical papers in major journals and conferences; several U.S. and international patents have been applied based on the inventions in this project;

- 9 PhD students and 4 MS students completed their theses based on related research in this project; 5 undergraduate students have conducted research in this project;

- Research findings from this project have been applied in the developement of new devices and systems for a wide range of applications in other related scientific and engineering areas;

- Research results from this project have been disseminated to industry and led to several new collaborative research and development (R&amp;D) activities;

- Conducted outreach to local and broader communities, including underrepresented minority and women students from University of Rochester's undergraduate student body and City of Rochester high schools.



